data.content:
Two separate breaking changes in C# 15:

---

**Issue 1 — `&&` with `dynamic`**

`&&` is a compound operator: it's synthesized from `operator &` + `operator true`/`operator false` (for short-circuiting). The compiler evaluates `left && right` as roughly `IFilter.false(left) ? left : IFilter.&(left, right)`.

`IFilter` declares `operator true`/`operator false` but **no `operator &`**. Previously, when `right` was `dynamic`, the compiler deferred the entire expression to the DLR at runtime. C# 15 now validates at compile time that the static type of the left operand has the complete set of operators needed to form `&&` — and `IFilter` is missing `operator &`.

**Fix options:**
```csharp
// Option A: Add operator & to the interface
interface IFilter
{
    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;
    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;
    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;
}

// Option B: Cast to concrete type to avoid the interface-level gap
void Apply(CompositeFilter left, dynamic right)
{
    var combined = left && right;  // OK — CompositeFilter has all three operators
}

// Option C: Avoid dynamic entirely
void Apply(IFilter left, IFilter right) { ... }
```

---

**Issue 2 — `ref readonly` return lambda (CS0518)**

CS0518 ("Predefined type is not defined or imported") means the compiler needs a well-known BCL type it can't find. C# 15 changed the metadata encoding for delegates with `ref readonly` returns — the synthesized delegate type now requires a new BCL attribute/type that isn't present in the runtime you're targeting.

This is an **SDK/runtime version mismatch**. Since .NET 11 is in preview, the compiler (SDK) and runtime must be the exact same preview band.

**Fix options:**
```csharp
// Option A: Align your SDK and runtime preview versions
// In your global.json + project TFM, ensure both are e.g. 11.0.0-preview.3

// Option B: Use an explicit delegate type (avoids compiler-synthesized delegate)
delegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();

public static void M()
{
    RefReadOnlyFunc fn = () => ref value;  // OK — no synthesized type needed
}
```
